description: Mango is a tropical fruit rich in fiber and vitamins. It’s enjoyed fresh, in juices, or as pickles.
Bananas are packed with potassium, B6, vitamin C, and fiber. Eaten raw or in shakes and desserts.
Apples are high in fiber and antioxidants. Linked to better heart and gut health.
Oranges are an excellent source of vitamin C. Supports immune and heart health.
Grapes are high in antioxidants like resveratrol. Eaten fresh or dried as raisins.
Papayas support digestion and immunity. Eaten ripe or in smoothies and salads.
Starchy tuber rich in potassium, B6, and fiber. Used in a variety of dishes.
Low-calorie but nutrient-dense. Used in almost all Indian dishes.
Rich in vitamin C and lycopene. Used in curries, chutneys, and salads.
High in fiber and vitamin C. Often used in stir-fries and curries.
Rich in fiber and antioxidants. Commonly used in bhindi masala or fried.
Excellent source of beta-carotene. Used in salads, curries, and sweets.
Fresh cow’s milk rich in calcium and protein. Used in tea, cereals, curds, and sweets.
Paneer is high in protein and calcium, used in dishes like palak paneer and butter masala.
Indian curd rich in calcium and probiotics. Eaten plain, with meals, or used in lassi.
Butter with fat-soluble vitamins adds flavor. Used as spread and in Indian cooking.
Lactose-free clarified butter valued in Indian cuisine and Ayurveda. High in nutrients.
Cheese rich in protein and calcium. Used in sandwiches, gravies, and snacks.
Crispy salted potato chips. Popular as tea-time or party snack.
Classic glucose biscuits. Often consumed with tea for quick energy.
Crunchy savory corn snack with spicy masala flavor.
Sweet cookies made with milk and wheat. Common tea-time snack.
Spiced gram flour sev mix. Eaten alone or in chaats.
Tangy corn and lentil crisps. Comes in flavors like tomato and peri-peri.
Nutrient-dense nuts rich in healthy fats, vitamin E, and protein. Eaten raw, roasted, or soaked.
Creamy nuts rich in heart-healthy fats, copper, and magnesium. Eaten as snacks or in dishes.
Dried grapes high in sugars and fiber. Provide energy; used in desserts and cereals.
Protein- and fiber-rich nuts. Help manage cholesterol. Often eaten roasted or in sweets.
Rich in omega-3 fats and antioxidants. Support brain health. Used raw or in cereals and sweets.
High in natural sugars, fiber, and potassium. Provide energy; often eaten to break fasts.
Strong Indian cola drink. Contains caffeine and sugar. Popular chilled beverage.
Black tea rich in antioxidants. Brewed daily in Indian homes for heart and gut health.
Instant coffee with caffeine and antioxidants. Supports energy and liver health.
Fruit juice rich in vitamin C. Refreshing drink made from mango pulp.
Packaged drinking water. Provides pure hydration essential for health.
Malted milk drink enriched with vitamins, minerals, and proteins. Often mixed with milk.
Lean, high-protein meat. Used in curries and grills. Provides all essential amino acids.
Lean red meat rich in protein and iron. Used in Indian biryani and mutton curry.
Freshwater fish high in protein and omega-3. Cooked as curry or fried.
Marine fish rich in lean protein and omega-3. Delicate taste, fried or grilled.
High-protein, low-fat seafood with omega-3. Used in prawn curry and biryani.
Fatty marine fish with firm texture. Common in coastal curries and kababs.
